{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645721"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:20:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:20:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18130"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18130"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.11,0,0.32,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73604"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73604"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the trabeculae in the trapezium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Support the articular surface of the bone","Act as a reservoir for bone marrow","Allow for the passage of nerves","Facilitate blood supply to the bone","Provide attachment for ligaments"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe trabeculae within the trapezium, as with other bones, are part of the spongy bone structure that provides internal support and strength. They help to support the \u003Cstrong\u003Earticular surface of the bone\u003C/strong\u003E, which is crucial for the function of the carpometacarpal joint of the thumb. This joint is essential for thumb movement and grip strength.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding attachment for ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of the bone\u0027s outer surface, not the trabeculae. Ligaments attach to the periosteum, the outer fibrous layer of the bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitating blood supply\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the role of the bone\u0027s vascular system, including the nutrient arteries and the periosteum, rather than the trabeculae themselves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllowing for the passage of nerves\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of the trabeculae. Nerves typically run alongside blood vessels in the periosteum and through the bone\u0027s nutrient foramina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActing as a reservoir for bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of the medullary cavity in long bones, not the trabeculae in the carpal bones like the trapezium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The trapezium is one of the carpal bones in the wrist, located on the radial side of the hand.","The trapezium articulates with the first metacarpal bone, forming the carpometacarpal joint of the thumb.","The trabeculae of the trapezium are part of its internal structure, providing strength and support."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18130"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T00:31:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T00:32:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10844"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73604"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null